rth Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Graham","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from Grantham in Lincolnshire, recorded in Domesday Book as <i>Graham</i> (as well as <i>Grantham</i>, <i>Grandham</i>, and <i>Granham</i>). See also   Grantham  .","Irish (especially Ulster): in Ireland <i>Graham</i> is generally the Scottish name, but it has additionally been adopted as an Anglicized form of both <b>Ó Creacháin</b> (see   Crehan  ) and <b>Ó Gormghaile</b> (see   Gormley  ).","History: The surname Graham was taken to Scotland at the beginning of the 12th century by the Norman baron William de Graham, holder of the manor of Grantham in Lincolnshire, from whom many if not all modern bearers are probably descended. The chief of Clan Graham is the Duke of Montrose."],"variants":[{"name":"Greim","meanings":["South German: from a short form of a compound personal name beginning with the element <i>grīm</i> ‘mask, helmet’.","Scottish: variant of   Graham  ."]},{"name":"Grahm","meanings":["(1997: 107;2007: 460; 2010: NA)","Scottish (Lanarkshire and northern England): shortened form of   Graham  ."]},{"name":"Grantham","meanings":["English (Lincolnshire and East Yorkshire): habitational name from Grantham in Lincolnshire, of uncertain origin. The final element is Old English <i>hām</i> ‘homestead’; the first may be Old English <i>grand</i> ‘gravel’ or perhaps a personal name <i>Granta</i>, which probably originated as a byname meaning ‘snarler’. See also   Graham  ."]},{"name":"Grahame","meanings":["(1997: 113;2007: 164; 2010: NA)","Scottish: variant of   Graham  . — Note: The population figure published by the US Census Bureau for this surname in the year 2000 is as high as 261, while the figure for 2010 is supposedly lower than 100."]}]},{"name":"Alan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705183,"age":6,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","description":"Domesday Book is Britain's earliest extant public record with information containing land surveys and landholdings commissioned by William I. The book was completed in 1086.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/domesday/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Domesday","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705184,"age":16,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705185,"age":26,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Alan de Graham was born in 1080, in Grantham, Lincolnshire, England, his father, William de Graham of Abercorn and Dalkeith, was 31 and his mother, Emmalina Bretagne, was 29. He had at least 1 son with Lucia Mercia Ramera. He died about 1130, in Dalkeith, Midlothian, Scotland, at the age of 51."},"et":{"1080–about 1130":"1080–umbes 1130","1072–Male":"1072–Surnud","1080–1130":"1080–1130","1070–1144":"1070–1144","1097–1139":"1097–1139","1049–1095":"1049–1095","1051–Female":"1051–Surnud","1080":"1080","1086":"1086","1097":"1097","1130":"1130","1096":"1096","1095":"1095","1051":"1051","1072":"1072","1070":"1070","Abt 1097":"umbes 1097","1106":"1106","1139":"1139","1049":"1049","1144":"1144","about 1130":"umbes 1130","Dalkeith, Midlothian, Scotland":"Dalkeith, Midlothian, Scotland","Grantham, Lincolnshire, England":"Grantham, Lincolnshire, England"},"fi":{"1080–about 1130":"1080–noin 1130","1072–Male":"1072–Kuollut","1080–1130":"1080–1130","1070–1144":"1070–1144","1097–1139":"1097–1139","1049–1095":"1049–1095","1051–Female":"1051–Kuollut","1080":"1080","1086":"1086","1097":"1097","1130":"1130","1096":"1096","1095":"1095","1051":"1051","1072":"1072","1070":"1070","Abt 1097":"noin 1097","1106":"1106","1139":"1139","1049":"1049","1144":"1144","about 1130":"noin 1130","Dalkeith, Midlothian, Scotland":"Dalkeith, Midlothian, Scotland","Grantham, Lincolnshire, England":"Grantham, Lincolnshire, England"},"fr":{"1080–about 1130":"1080–environ 1130","1072–Male":"1072–Décédé","1080–1130":"1080–1130","1070–1144":"1070–1144","1097–1139":"1097–1139","1049–1095":"1049–1095","1051–Female":"1051–Décédée","1080":"1080","1086":"1086","1097":"1097","1130":"1130","1096":"1096","1095":"1095","1051":"1051","1072":"1072","1070":"1070","Abt 1097":"environ 1097","1106":"1106","1139":"1139","1049":"1049","1144":"1144","about 1130":"environ 1130","Dalkeith, Midlothian, Scotland":"Dalkeith, Midlothian, Écosse","Grantham, Lincolnshire, England":"Grantham, Lincolnshire, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Alan de Graham est né en 1080, à Grantham, Lincolnshire, Angleterre, son père, William de Graham of Abercorn and Dalkeith, avait 31 ans et sa mère, Emmalina Bretagne, avait 29 ans. Il a eu au moins 1 f